CFC Kansas City, April 16/88
C.B&L.RR.
Sir:
In continuation of the above operation
My operator G.F.G. further reports as follows: 
Saturday, April 14/88 - "I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. and proceeded to the [?Amire} Depot. Upon my arrival at the depot I strolled through the yards and conversed with the employees and found that they apprehended no further trouble at present. The idea heretofore unclear that the Brotherhood was unclear is gradually wearing away and some think that the strikers will have to succeed The new men on the switch engines are becoming more familiar with the yards and consequently there is not so much grumbling among the switchmen as when they first come out. Noticing a policeman

on a Hannibal engine I said to a switchman: "I see that the new men still have a body guard." His reply was: "Yes, I - unclear, they need them too" A policemen on a "2" engine is no figurehead. He is an actual necessity and will be for some time." 
Everything was quiet and orderly about the yards and I saw nor heard nothing that would lead me to suspect further trouble at present." 
My operator H.E. reports as follows: 
Thursday, April 12/88
"At 3 p.m. I left the Agency for the purpose of getting such information as W.H Courtney, a patrolman on Capt. McGraw's force was reports to have concurring the assault that was made upon two of the employees of the C.B. & 2 RR in the Whittakers restaurant the morning of April 1st. I called upon Capt. McGraw but did not find him at his office. I saw his clerk and informed him of the business I was upon. He informed me the patrolman Courtney would not report until late in the evening.

but when he did he (the clerk) would learn all he could from him relation to what he might know fo the assault. i then as per appointment proceeded to the Union Depot and called at the office of Mr. Fish. He not being in I waited until nearly 5 p.m. On his not returning I returned to the Agency and at 6:30 p.m. I again called at the office of Capt. McGraw. I saw the clerk. He informed me he had seen Officer Courtney and he had said he did not see the assault, but he believe he  could identify the man, as this was not in accordance with his assertions. I asked the clerk to request Capt. McGraw to speak to Courtney and endeavor to get all the information he could from him. I arranged to call again and see the Capt. I then returned to the Agency." 
My Operator G.F.G. further reports: 
Sunday, April 15th/88
"I left the Agency at 8:30 a.m. and proceeded to Union Depot. After arriving at the depot I walked through the yards and found every-

thing quiet and orderly. In conversing with the switchmen I find that they remember how the striking engineers acted during the switchmens' strike some time since. The switchmen claim that the switch engineers at that time instead of attending strictly to their own line of business also performed the duties of the switchmen. Many railroad men think the unclear stand taken by the "2" road in the present contest will be a great help towards preventing railroad strikes in the future. They also think that had the company yielded to the demands of the strikers trouble would be likely to occur in other departments during the summer. There is a growing belief that the strikers will, before a great while, come back and ask to be re-instated in their former positions and agree to the terms and conditions that the company has dictated." 
Yours respectfully,
Pinkertons Natl. Detective Agency
W.A. Pinkerton
unclear Supt. W.D.
